Help

To get info how to use Unix you can

* read Nada www information
* use the command "local-info"
* use the commands "apropos subject" och "man subject"

Initialization files

ENGLISH-SPEAKING?
If you prefer English dialogs in programs, and information
in English (when avaliable), then se to it that
the environment variable LANG has the value "en_US". This
is initialized by default for English-speaking users (since
sept. 1996) in the file ".environment". (Can be copied from
/usr/local/etc/nadaskel/en/.environment.)
In your directory there are some files which don't show up when you do
an ordinary ls. They all begin with ".", you have to do "ls -a" to see
them.

These files set up your environment. When you are more used to everything,
you can change them to your own taste. But leave them alone to start 
with, otherwise things may get confusing...

At Nada we use the command interpreter (shell) "tcsh".
Before your personal files, common files in
/usr/local/etc/shellinits are run, see below.

Originally you have the following initialization files in your directory:

.login          Run *only* at text login (i.e. Telnet
                etc.). Before this the file  
                /usr/local/etc/shellinits/login.init is run.
.tcshrc         Run when the tcsh-shell is started. (also at login)
                Runs .cshrc. Before this the file
                /usr/local/etc/shellinits/tcsh.init is run.
 ...
                This command file sets up emacs and other programs
                (clisp, prolog) so that they are restarted if you have
                left them suspended.  This way you wont get lots of
                emacses if you leave emacs with ^X^Z. Also the time to
                restart emacs is much shorter than to start it from
                fresh.
 ...
.cshrc          This is run whenever you start a new csh-shell. As .tcshrc
                invokes it, it is run every time you start a new tcsh also.
.aliases        In this file you can specify aliases for often used
                commands. This file is loaded from
                /usr/local/etc/shellinits/tcsh.init.
...
.environment    This is a good place to define your environment
                variables. This file too is loaded by
                /usr/local/etc/shellinits/tcsh.init.
...
.modules        Here you can specify which modules you want
                initially in a session. This is also loaded by 
                /usr/local/etc/shellinits/tcsh.init.

There are several other possible initialization files used by different
programs. Only some are mentioned here. For examples of how they 
might look, check the directory "/usr/local/etc/shellinits/examples".

.Xresources_hook  From Nadas standard .xinitrc this file is send to
                the xrdb program ("X Resource Manager Database"). This
                database handles e.g. the foreground and background
                colors, and default fonts, for most X programs. Thus
                this is the place to specify if you want a special
                font in e.g. emacs, or a special background color of
                e.g. the clock.
.xinitrc_hook   This file is loaded from the standard .xinitrc at
                NADA. Here you can specify e.g. the background color
                of the screen, and start some additional programs if
                you are not satisfied with the ones you normally get
                initially. 
.xinitrc        If you are not at all satisfied with the default
                X-environment, then you can have your own .xinitrc
                file. However, this requires that you know what you
                are doing. Check the example file in 
                /usr/local/etc/shellinits/examples. 
.mwmrc          Used by MWM (Motif Window Manager). Here you can
                specify for example window colors, and the contents of
                window manager menus.
 
.emacs          Run whenever GNU Emacs (normal emacs) is loaded. Here
                you can specify various emacs variables, and determine
                which functions are bound to which keys.
.mailrc         Read when you start the mail program. Makes it always 
                ask for subject and always save your own
                messages into the "mbox" file on your directory.
.logout         Run just before you are logged out.

After some sessions these files may appear (amongst others):

mbox            Where your letters are saved (mailbox).
.newsrc         Read when the network news read program is started.
                Use "rn", not "vnews"!

The file you are now reading is a so called symbolic link
to the global file 
/usr/local/etc/nadaskel/sv/README.
You can remove the link with the command "rm README".

If you should do some foolish thing with some of the init-files, 
you can always retrieve the original from
the directory /usr/local/etc/nadaskel/en/.
    

**Good luck!**

